Matthis stepped inside the Oak and Ember and dripped next to the door. The air was moist but warm. The fire spat in the giant hearth. The place was packed. He heard loud guffaws from one table that sounded like donkey brays.

"When I says yer an ass, I didn't think you'd become one!"

"I think he should be in charge of the mule team today, boys."

The braying laughter was almost drowned out by cries of surprise from a group gathered around a deck of playing cards.

"Luckiest hand I've seen, that was."

"You cheat. I can't believe you won again."

"Don't be like that. I'm just smarter than you lot."

One of the players was Rafe. "Been a while since I've lost like that," he said. "Care for another hand?"

Matthis scanned the room for red curly hair. He squeezed between the benches and dripped next to the fire. One of the pots threatened to boil over. He glanced toward the kitchen and nudged the crane with the poker. The boil calmed to a simmer. He checked the pile of wood in one corner. Only large pieces left. 

No one but Matthis heard the little squeal from the kitchen over the din. He slipped his head inside and saw Aura sitting in a pile of flour and holding the bag in front of her. Elspeth's usual hair kerchief was gone. She repeatedly clawed strands away from her eyes. 

"Aura," she said, her voice strained, "I asked you please don't touch that." Aura's lip quivered. 

Matthis checked the pots on the fire again. They smelled of herbs with chicken and vegetables. His hand hesitated by the ladle that hung from the mantle. He pulled his hand away. Instead, he squeezed between the benches again and plunged outside. 

He rounded the building to the back. A pile of round blocks stood against the wall. A sloped roof shielded them from the rain. An axe hung from a nail on the wall above them. He set about splitting the blocks. 

The rain made the haft a little slippery. But he adjusted his grip and set a block onto a chopping stump. Set, swing, gather. Before long, he had a neat pile. He bent and lifted a few. 

"What are you doing."

Elspeth stood at the corner of the house, her hair frizzled around her head. Her hand was on her heart. Her cheeks were white. "Why are you chopping logs, Matthis."

Arms full of wood, Matthis faced her. Her eyes were a brighter green than usual. Water streamed down her face. Her lips were red. Her eyes didn't leave his as he stepped forward and stood next to her. 

"I didn't want you to do it alone."

They stood there in the rain. One of her hands gripped the hem of her apron. She held the other over her heart. 

"I thought you were Father," she said.

The rain pattered on both of them. Matthis didn't look away. Neither did she. 

"It's been years, Matthis." Her voice broke. "Years and years."

Matthis shifted the wood in his arms. He touched her cheek. Her hand lifted to his. Her mouth opened a little, and her eyes widened.

"He's at peace," said Matthis. "But you're not alone. Elspeth." He felt her shiver. "You're not alone."

He nodded and began to pull away. She touched his arm. He stopped and faced her again. They stood there for a moment. His fingers rested on her cheek. She squeezed his hand. Not all the water on her face was rain. 

Matthis smiled. Elspeth gasped and reached up. She hesitated and almost pulled her hand away. She searched his eyes and then slowly, gently extended her fingers and touched his lips. She whispered. 

"How long has it been since I've seen you smile?"

Matthis stroked her cheek and said nothing. 

--

Arms folded, Matthis leaned against the wall next to the wood pile and listened to the pub. Elspeth bustled from one table to another.

"Ellie. Your soup is divinity, it is."

Elspeth barked a dry laugh, four more bowls balanced on her arms. Not a drop spilled. "Have you told that to the Vicar, Alek?"

The braying donkey laugh started up again. His friends cajoled him.

"No more ale for this one, okay, Ellie?"

"You know miner's should never drink until the day's shift ends, right? We still have half the day left."

"I haven't had any ale -- hic -- honest. It's all this -- hic -- laughing what's done it."

Everyone on Rafe's table roared and cards slammed on the tabe. Some men exclaimed in loud amusement, others in frustration.

"I never seen someone win like that, Rafe."

"How's a ruddy gravedigger winning like this," one man grumbled into his empty bowl of soup. 

Rafe threw back his head and laughed. "I can't believe I'm this lucky today."

Several threw down their cards and pounded their knees. But Rafe soon had everyone at his laughing again.

Elspeth's hair kerchief was back. Matthis watched her slide between the benches with ease as she pulled empty bowls off the table. He thought she snuck a look at him through her hair, but he couldn't tell for sure.

A miner tapped her elbow as she passed.

"Do you know why we come here, maid Ellie, and not the guild house, maid Ellie?" The man's eyes were permanently crossed. Matthis pictured him in the coal yard with a hammer.

Elspeth smiled. "Why is that, Brim?"

A lopsided smile spread across the man's pockmarked face. "It's right nice here, maid Ellie, right nice. Right tasty, your food is."

she patted his shoulder. "You are all welcome here any time." She wove her way to the kitchen with smooth movements, a stack of bowls in each arm.

The sound of the Pit Bell caused total havoc. Three men yelled, threw back their heads, and drained their soup in a single gulp. The building rumbled. All the benches slid away from the tables at once. Men streamed out of the building.

"Beautiful nosh, Ellie."

"This game is not finished, Rafe."

"I -- hic -- swear, if you call me an ass one more -- hic -- time ..."

"Thanks for the food, Ellie!"

"Tom, you forgot to leave your stupid axe behind again, didn't you?"

"We'll be back tonight, Ellie."

"I just had Foss sharpen it the other day. Wasn't about to let it rust, was I?"

"I like coming here, maid Ellie, I do. The food, it's right nice in the stomach. Right tasty food."

"Thanks for keeping us warm, Ellie!"

Elspeth set bread and cheese wrapped in cloth into Matthis' hand. He hadn't noticed her sneak up on him. He fished in his satchel for his money pouch. 

"It's okay, Matthis," she whispered.

She took the parcel placed it into his bag. He took her hand and held it in his. He found her eyes. 

"Thank you, Elspeth." He gently squeezed and let go.

They held their look for a moment. Fire hissed in the hearth. She smiled. He tried to smile back, but his lips hurt. Her smile widened. 

A spoon dropped in the kitchen. Elspeth spun and hurried into the kitchen Hair spilled out of her kerchief. He watched her lift Aura and set her on a table in the kitchen. 

Outside, the rain had stopped. The chill bit through his coat. He shivered and drew it tight. He liked the weight of Elspeth's bread in his satchel.